docs.abstract: References to “2001: A Space Odyssey,” “The Night of the Hunter” and “Carnival of Souls” are seen in a recent hour of Mr. Lynch’s revival.
docs.snippet: References to “2001: A Space Odyssey,” “The Night of the Hunter” and “Carnival of Souls” are seen in a recent hour of Mr. Lynch’s revival.
docs.lead_paragraph: The artist and filmmaker David Lynch has an uncanny ability to create work that doesn’t just evoke dread and discomfort — it can make a viewer actually feel that dread and discomfort. “Lynch is a director of mood and texture, the queasier the better,” the critic J. Hoberman observed back in 1984. In the same piece, Mr. Hoberman proclaimed that Mr. Lynch “may be the American director with the most direct pipeline to his unconscious.” These traits are explicitly evident in “Twin Peaks: The Return,” the extraordinary limited series — or 18-hour movie, as Mr. Lynch would have it; he’s divided it into “parts” rather than “episodes” — now unspooling on Showtime, and its attendant streaming site and app Showtime Now.

headline.main: David Lynch Weaves Film History Into ‘Twin Peaks: The Return’
headline.print_headline: Past and Present Meet In Today’s ‘Twin Peaks’
